                <head>No. 668.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Fish</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Evarts</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Berne</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1881-01-10">
                            <hi rend="italic">January</hi> 10, 1881</date>. (Received January
                        26.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 326.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Gazette de Lausanne of Friday evening
                    contains a notice to the effect that the commune of Gersau, in the canton of
                    Sehwytz, is, owing to the scarcity of work, compelled to assist its citizens to
                    emigrate, and that it has voted a subsidy of 250 francs to those over eighteen
                    years who emigrate, and 100 francs to their children over ten, and 30 francs to
                    those under ten years of age.</p>
                <p>The Bund of this morning contains a similar statement. I inclose copies of both
                    of these notices, with translations thereof herewith.</p>
                <p>I have instructed Consul Byers to inquire and report concerning the action of the
                    authorities of Gersau.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>NICHOLAS FISH.</signed>
                </closer>
                <pb facs="1231" n="1107" xml:id="pg_1107"/>
                <frus:attachment>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#center">[Inclosure in No. 326.—Translation.]</seg>
                    </opener>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">Extract from Der Bund, Berne, January</hi> 10,
                        1881.</head>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schwytz</hi>.—The citizens of Gersau appear inclined to
                        solve the social question through a possible assistance to emigration. The
                        commune recently adopted a resolution to furnish every citizen who would
                        emigrate, who had attained his eighteenth year, 250 francs for his journey;
                        citizens from ten to eighteen years receive 100 francs; for children under
                        ten years of age an allowance of 30 francs is reckoned.</p>
                </frus:attachment>
            </div>
